Barack Obama to be the fourth US President to receive Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours and be the fourth American President in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be awarded to him, among other things, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have a busy program.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the very first time the five members of the Committee who selected him in October among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then included an interview with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He would be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third who would be awarded the prize in the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan when the award was presented.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at the moment.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to stress.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of 10 million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate it to charitable organizations, but has not yet decided in concrete terms which ones.
His busy program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the Head of Government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant to pay that price at first.
He mentioned, for example, that he felt that he was not fully deserving of it.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for him alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was made, he said that it would be an "invitation to act."
