United States: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the strenuous effort with which Barack Obama, President with the reputation of being wise, reproduces his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan question, which he himself considered to be very simple.
When he finally let his longed-for doctrine sweat, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush's Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the phrase "as in Iraq," he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by the civil war as "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to be so successful that newspapers at present do not speak of Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, however, objectively speaking, he left his successor a much more favourable final situation than could be expected.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will recur
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him to increase the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
It succeeded in extracting the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems in Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies of Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. Obama's whole doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that an increase of half will bring the same results as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the exact opposite - no one can be relied on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their leadership on a day-to-day basis, according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing but powder in the eye behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in the light of the lack of clarity in relations, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "prompt state to act," which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is puzzled by his wildness.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out of reality heart can be convinced that the small soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "quick return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for the withdrawal of troops is simply irresponsible, as the Taliban will consider it an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the will of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning negative.
European policies do not know or want to explain to their constituents how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of Hindu Kush.
Another factor that can radically alter the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not affect the Iranian people, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America comes to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution would, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only rustin for Obama is the fact that three years remain until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
