Czech discovery: a substance that works on HIV viruses "enduring" as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also affects viruses that have already developed immunity to medicines.
This reality takes precedence, in some cases, over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, life can be radically extended through a mixture of medicines that prevent the spread of HIV in the body.
However, there are a number of side effects associated with their use.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing so-called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg, paves the way for dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein that multiplies the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a way different from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their binding on virus proteins.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous, resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles of the virus.
If we stop the protease of HIV, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
