The Chinese authorities had assigned the duty to the police to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers had denounced abuses in the implementation of that policy.
In rural areas, some government officials forced pregnant women from a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys to girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the single child policy.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already unique children -- and in 2007, they softened many of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
Within no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of detailed regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for authorization.
The city government has sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their homes and drag leaflets under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the family planning officer, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural suburb of Shanghai say they saw an increase in requests for couples' files seeking a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Family Planning Committee in the municipality of Caolu, Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed to have two children.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners wrongly consider the one-child policy a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
That's right, we're being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Head of Human Resources, said she wanted only one child because she was one of her own. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us."
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company says so crudely.
For middle-class couples working with each other, who lower the birth rate, he says, one must be selfish to succeed.
People aged 20 or 30 grew up watching their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and do not want to have this lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even one child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are space problems -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his résumé to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, says Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to enjoy a higher standard of living, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back under the spotlight on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden, in the next few years.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as far as it informed the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that are running out of time, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Written by an ad hoc United Nations working group, the text did not say how rich countries would give the poor to cope with global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how new developed and emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be prepared to tolerate.
It gives the process great flexibility, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the paper, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete picture."
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent of 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
On Friday, however, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Climate Negotiation Representative, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China's Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, He Yafei said that the US chief negotiator, either lacked "common sense," or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not help China financially to combat global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of taking more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers were struggling to find out who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even if vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Insular States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of the small island states "put political pressure on the complete political process," in part by what they are now unified and that they are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the Heads of Government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister came down from their aircraft and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be investigated in the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- in which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des Congrès every day -- guitar players present night shows mocking the countries they think are betraying themselves and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by e-mail -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the heart of the great, "said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President for Global Conservation Policy International.
The trucks are coming.
