Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, just over a year after Moscow recognized this pro-Russian separatist region of Georgia, while Tbilisi denounced a "farce."
Some 131,000 people were expected to participate in this first election after the Russian-Georgian war of August 2008 for the control of South Ossetia, another secessionist Georgian territory recognized by Russia.
The polling stations closed at 1700 GMT.
The turnout was 58 per cent a few hours before the closure, according to officials of the Abkhaz Electoral Commission.
The first provisional results were to be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
