The court of Nanterre decided Friday to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine whether, as the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt accuses him, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenarian to strip her of part of his fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photos of stars, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, an offence punishable by up to three years' imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will indeed be a trial in this case worthy of a saga on one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter are torn apart while holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetic empire.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical examination of 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt should be conducted collegially by three doctors.
The heir and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office at the time of the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will have to submit a report by 10 March 2010, including whether and when Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness.
I think she'll submit to it.
I will tell him about it, said at the end of the hearing Ms. Bettencourt's lawyer, Me Georges Kiejman.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news (...) Expertise will show that he (Mr. Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who needs to be protected, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has been suing François-Marie Banier, photographer and artist-at-all, for having used her mother's weakness for years to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted having been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers to be a long-time friend.
While the court was to consider the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers' action, the lawyers' pleadings sometimes turned to a big family deballage on Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer referred to three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to counsel: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I've never been able to talk to her since she was married. "
For her part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office again held that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge had refused in recent days to grant her request to initiate judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full legal capacity, is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place, "said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would rule once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter of getting employees to adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, of imposing on consumers products conceived by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back on the spot... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preferences regularly returns!
Demoralization of employees can lead to mortifying demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R & D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
EI "demands a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision from all stakeholders..." and requires a commitment on the part of employees, which authoritarian management revenues completely frustrate.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys - such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees - encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally comes, after many detours, to do first... what it has always done.!
- Then, because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
From the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the commitment of managers, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr helps the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, not adapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists of incorporating a fundamental observation into any governance reasoning or practice: for employees, commitment to the enterprise is only possible if it is clearly seen as a means of achieving part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them in order to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business managers can monitor, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and return their human resources management "to the place."
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: "Just War" Worth Praise on the Right to Obama
On Friday, the American right welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the day before, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who embroidered the award to Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice-president candidate in the 2008 elections.
I liked what he said, "said Palin, a member of the right wing of the Republican party, to the daily USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the subject of war" sometimes necessary "in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be arrested all over the country, she said.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Mr. Obama, Newt Gingrich, felt that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I found the speech really very good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed during the radio show "The Takeaway."
The former elected member, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind Nobel Committee members "that they would not be free and would not be able to give a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush, reconverted columnist at the Washington Post, Obama gave "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does," "he spoke like an American president," reminding Europeans "that they live in a safety bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it," Gerson said.
Among the few on the right not to be convinced, a Bush-era falcon, former UN Ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as "dull, muddled and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
On the left of the President, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich alarmed that Barack Obama justified the use of force.
When we wrap war in the notion of justice, we can easily justify the killing of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, continued to praise the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was prematurely awarded to Mr. Obama, described his speech as "superproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the California daily.
Obama "gave the right speech," the New York Times said, judging him "both dark and edifying."
Roads: three marathons for an agreement that saves Christmas supplies
After three sessions of negotiations-marathon, the road trade unions and TLF, the only employers' organisation to have stayed to the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that ended the slogan of strike and the threat to Christmas supplies.
At the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, welcomed this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, which began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators had left in the early morning of Friday, hoping to sign the agreement text quickly at the end of the morning.
Even though three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slapped the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting started at 11: 00 a.m. for everyone to agree and at 6: 00 p.m. the text was signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "there was a fear that it would disrupt the end-of-year holidays," Mr. Bussereau said.
The text provides for an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wages (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low-wage earners, "from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we're going a long way, "said Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we're going to order our militants that there are no blockages, no blockades from the refuelling centres.
But we can still have some recalcitrant people who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, President of TLF, welcomed "a good deal," although it was "difficult to concede increases on high wages given the international competition."
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest ones.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement."
Richard Jaubert (CGT) referred to "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and the maintenance of general road transport conditions in the first half of 2010, which will make it possible, inter alia, to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernisation of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of EUR 100 million in employers' costs" was the subject of a government amendment to the draft amending finance law for 2009, which was voted by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government will ask the Senate to vote it "in identical terms."
The signing of the TLF allows the agreement to apply initially to enterprises belonging to that organisation, and secondly to the whole profession, in the event of extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be "as soon as possible," Mr Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupe market," as the €100 million "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax."
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, Unostra deplored.
For the West, the agreement risks "digging down the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months."
RER A: Disturbances this weekend, unions dissatisfied with RATP proposals
Disturbances on the RER A, France's largest urban transit line, will continue over the weekend, while a meeting on Friday on the 2nd day of strike between unions and RATP management left them on their hunger for their premium request.
Saturday and Sunday, for this important shopping weekend before Christmas, there will only be trains between 10: 00 a.m. and 8: 00 p.m., with one train out of two on the central section (between La Défense and Nation) and one train out of four outside the central section.
Interconnection with SNCF will be suspended at Nanterre Préfecture, which will require passengers to switch trains.
The Lafayette Galleries, which expect 200,000 customers every day, welcomed the fact that "RATP is making efforts to serve department stores."
The RER A crosses from west to east the Paris agglomeration.
The RATP section runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, about one in two trains ran during peak hours, and almost no trains in off-peak hours, as expected.
As on Thursday, there was no cohue on the docks, the Franciens having organized themselves.
Thus in the early morning, the station of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less frequented than usual, especially because of the absence of high school students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), 29-year-old engineer Jack Nbakina explained that he had risen "an hour thirty before, to make sure he arrived on time."
Saint-Lazare station did not experience saturation, said SNCF, which had planned to train officers and law enforcement officers.
The RER A operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or left Saint-Lazare station to reach the metros.
New general meetings of strikers will be held on Saturday and Sunday to discuss the results of a meeting with management on Friday afternoon, which were deemed "lean" by the unions.
The RER Director proposes to negotiate a specific protocol for RER A on all aspects, working time, career development etc.
This is not what drivers want, who claim a bonus due, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even put its premium proposals in parentheses, outraged the CGT, pointing out that the management "was not doomed to solve a problem while among the truckers and the SNCF it was done."
A new meeting is scheduled for Monday for "a broader examination of the conditions of exercise of the profession," specified the RATP.
This also led the unions to say that the company "made fun of the weekend users."
In the morning, some 150 drivers had invaded an establishment committee at headquarters in Paris.
It was then that the management, which until then refused any discussion during the strike, had suggested "in the interest of appeasement" the meeting.
The conflict threatens to widen to the RER B on Tuesday, after the advance notice by Unsa and Independents.
The unions ask for a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros including 30 variable euros (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independent) and complain about the deterioration of working conditions on this line to the million daily passengers.
The drivers of RER, all in the second part of their career, receive between 2,200 and 2,700 euros gross and 600 to 650 euros in premiums for off-schedule hours, Sundays and public holidays.
Turkish justice dissolves the pro-Kurdish party, a decision that has far-reaching consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court declared the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just extended its hand to the Kurdish community in an attempt to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "hotbed of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity," the President of the Court Hasim Kiliç told the press, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to declare the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party's executives, including President Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabelled parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party assures that it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict comes at a time when the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, in an attempt to derail Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had claimed that a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the south-east of Anatolian, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the court was announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered outside the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the south-east, mostly populated by Kurds.
Law enforcement officers fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, as protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with swarms.
Some 100 people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk stated that the Justice decision would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, ndlr) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed, as a matter of principle, to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
One can, of course, expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a harsh winter.
But the person in charge of the road clearing and sandblasting service (FES) makes it clear that it is not to annoy the citizens.
It is simply so that agents can test the vehicle technique and learn to master it well.
And according to the meteorologists, it might be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to attack snow and ice.
The FES follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr Brauburger explained that as soon as it snows on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures fall below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel 20 main routes (known as Route A).
This includes traffic streets, main arteries, such as Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire-fighting access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
The officers of the FES begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometres of road must be salted with a road fondant that adheres well, within 3 hours of maximum time.
This is why the FES service starts at 3: 00 in the morning "so that the roads are cleared when the traffic of daily migrations begins."
Where it gets harder, it's when the snow starts falling at 7: 30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the road clearing and sandblasting department "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass through."
Then, if it does not snow, access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße - are taken care of.
Secondary lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger is well aware that this still causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES pedestrian team set off to identify as a priority the areas considered dangerous and the passages.
As for cycle paths, the services of the FES can generally not deal with them.
Mr Brauburger pointed out that there was a special department in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of bridges between 10 p.m. and 4: 30 a.m.
As ice is formed very quickly on these surfaces, the salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
The police may also call on this special service if necessary.
The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this bipod was about 2 metres long by 1.50m high, its posterior limbs were strong, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at that time was part of the land of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was on its way to the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa illuminates the evolution of the first dinosaurs in a new day.
In fact, he informs us about the kinship relationships, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt began excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team reports that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indians' word for the god of the sun.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms some theories concerning the early development of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, when the saurians divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor that appeared later and from which birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds on the long neck, and those related to them and the ornithisian herbivores of which species such as triceratops and stegosaurus belong.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found evidence that the Tawa hallae possessed small air bags in its skull, as did the birds that were the descendants of the Theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the related line of the huge saupods also possessed air bags and light frame, it may be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is to say, the entire land area that formed the Pangea supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, say researchers.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, paleontologist in Bonn says there is an even older species, silesaur, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a dinosaur-related group.
According to him this could give a misconception because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era, when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, is still a mystery today.
During the Triassic period, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the present crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread over the whole planet, promoting the development of many new species, while others, who were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs have survived randomly while other reptiles have disappeared.
Or else, dinosaurs were better suited and they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite encouraged the development of a group of animals which had also developed during the Triassic period and which since then had been in the shade: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley, California.
There are lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The evacuation by police from the casino at J.W. Goethe University in Frankfurt is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and teachers from J.W. Goethe University, as well as other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the Protestant students of Campus Westend.
In a statement written in German and English, they condemn the intervention of the police called for by the university's governing committee.
Last week, the President of the University Werner Müller-Estler had evacuated the buildings occupied by students and teachers of graffiti after walls and works of art had been burned with graffiti.
Five students were injured during the evacuation.
The signatories considered that the degradation did not justify "such violent intervention by the police commando against students and teachers who had organized their own courses."
Evacuation is an "unacceptable attack" on freedom of research and education.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism serves only to "delegitimize and criminalize protest" and attempts to obscure the reasons for mobilization.
The Governing Committee of the University has thus evaded the discussions which would be indispensable.
The trial officers demand that the criminal proceedings instituted be immediately suspended.
The majority of the occupants did not take part in the damage.
Legitimation of protests
The young people of the Verdi trade union in the services sector and the German Confederation of Trade Unions (DGB) show solidarity with the students.
Protests are only a legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Alexander Klein, Verdi's regional youth secretary.
As for the Minister of Science of the Land of Hesse Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU), she has taken up the cause of the action taken by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and deterioration of the place is totally unacceptable, she told the Wiesbaden Regional Parliament last Thursday during the television show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, said CDU Member of the Regional Parliament Peter Beuth.
The opposition parliamentary groups SPD, the Greens and the Left (die Linke) did not share this view.
The CSU takes the pretext of some painted walls to criminalize the protests, said Janine Wissler of the Left Party (Linke)
Instead of reflecting on the students' arguments and demands, they are removed.
The Left Party has tabled a motion to the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on the conditions of police intervention.
The new "Silicon-valley"
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place for the search for secret weapons under strict surveillance.
Today, with 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the town has a reputation as the Soviet Silicon Valley.
There are important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, the centre of the French-speaking sciences - with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of close cooperation."
The signatories were Vice Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz Head of Project Section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose main focus is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a long-term scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific companies wish to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the headquarters of famous Soviet research institutes and companies.
There is the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the large companies Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") takes its name from the wooded hills in the heart of which the research centres are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be set high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than "the new heart of Europe."
If you want. S21, it is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, into a hopeless chaos of construction sites for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
Headline stations, with tracks ending in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being relics of 19th-century transport technology that acted as a brake shoe for modern rail traffic because it used to take a long time to move locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure - that's what we have to do.
That is why head-end stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train station, which is about half way on the Trans-European Rail Magistrate between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe."
The implementation of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s have long been incompatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, head-of-line stations no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and driver cars at both ends.
However, the realization of Stuttgart 21 is now being launched next to the new route of the inter-city line towards Ulm.
Regional and communal policies have won.
The railway company is on the side because it is the taxpayer who bears the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public enterprise.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
An urban space is obtained which - based on computer-generated planners' graphs - will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and the widening of the section are designed for a traffic of people that was attributed - and this is typical of the 1980s - a huge growth.
At the time there was still no competition for cheap flights.
