It is surprising to note that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that treat sensory perceptions, are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain is heating but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this state as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, pain of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one third of participants acknowledged having experienced a hallucination at least once in their life.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. was 16 years old and lived in a small town in Mecklenburg-Pomerania and went to high school.
A young girl everything to do normal, actually.
If there weren't images and voices.
During recess, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long chestnut hair, speaks to him.
When she answers her comrades look at her, amazed - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer but Sarah K doesn't dream, she's sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even perceive her presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she thinks this young guy is nice.
Am I crazy?, she wonders sometimes.
But she knows well that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Often visions are burdensome.
When she is in class, she may not be able to take the course because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations to the table.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for sleep that happens too rarely and far too late, she often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dreams already, if the images she sees, the faces grim or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she screams to these creatures.
She doesn't talk about it to her parents or friends, they'd think she was crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and lives with her friend.
A year ago, hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she came into Internet contact with psychologist Kasten, she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, there is a high probability that they will have hallucinations after some time.
I guess the brain's not busy enough, making sure there's some animation.
Sarah K., a single girl, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she called Dad, since she was old enough to think, was not her real father.
It is the same brain zones that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and sounds, it is therefore very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real. "
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That's why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There's only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness, unfortunately, there is a rapid tendency to take imaginary experiments for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief doctor of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence Nightingale hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease but it also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the form of the so-called oniroid experience, a particular form of changing consciousness awakened by the dream.
The oniroid lives are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies, as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and of the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that harms his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It's a state of mental limitation between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world is taking place, but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity which is given to us, men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
The Zurichois Peter Cornelius Classen, an art historian, also describes his oniriid experiences in his book "Change of heart" as an action to save the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious leaves for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain still in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he created from scratch, visits foreign places, travels through time. He sees himself as an old man living in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside looking after his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the Neve of the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
He absorbs himself completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental travels are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience brings out the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, the oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a state of sleep.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summed up psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
