75% of working mothers have had occupational problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and career of women in Spain," carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional career limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of a couple's life and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not, and the type of employment.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or work with little stability, enter into a relationship earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back entry into marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a significant influence on maternity, but less on the date of the start of common life, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the gap between the marriage age of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those with elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, "says Delgado.
