The emergency brake assist works by increasing the brake pressure in case of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident were unable to press the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take full advantage of its force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revancha, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four casualties with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, by means of a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, as well as acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
